    • Method Detail

      • getAngles

        public static double[] getAngles(boolean toJ2000,
                 double JD,
                 EphemerisElement eph)
                          throws JPARSECException
        Get precession angles.
        Parameters:
        toJ2000 - True to precess to J2000, false for from J2000.
        JD - Julian day of the output angles.
        eph - Ephemeris properties.
        Returns:
        Array with the three precession angles (pA, omega, i) in the ecliptic, or with the precession angles (psiA, omegaA, chiA, EPS0) in the equator for IAU2000 and later resolutions.
        Throws:
        JPARSECException - If the reduction method is not supported.

      • precessionVondrak2011

        public static double[] precessionVondrak2011(double JD0,
                             double JD,
                             double[] R)
                                      throws JPARSECException
        Precession following Vondrak et al. 2011. See A&A 534, A22.
        Parameters:
        JD0 - Julian day of input vector (equatorial rectangular).
        JD - Julian day of output. Either JD or JD0 must be equal to Constant.J2000.
        R - Input vector.
        Returns:
        Vector referred to mean equinox and equator of JD.
        Throws:
        JPARSECException - If JD and JD0 are non equal to J2000.

      • FK5_JxxxxToFK4_Bxxxx

        public static double[] FK5_JxxxxToFK4_Bxxxx(double[] eq,
                            double jdFK5,
                            double jdFK4,
                            EphemerisElement eph)
                                     throws JPARSECException
        Transforms FK5 coordinates to FK4, supposing that the object has no proper motion or is far away. The equinoxes for the input/output positions can be selected.
        Parameters:
        eq - Equatorial coordinates FK5 Jxxxx.
        jdFK5 - The equinox for the input equatorial coordinates.
        jdFK4 - The equinox desired for the output FK4 coordinates.
        eph - The ephemeris object selecting the precession algorithms.
        Returns:
        FK4 Bxxxx coordinates.
        Throws:
        JPARSECException - Should not be thrown.

      • FK4_BxxxxToFK5_Jxxxx

        public static double[] FK4_BxxxxToFK5_Jxxxx(double[] eq,
                            double jdFK5,
                            double jdFK4,
                            EphemerisElement eph)
                                     throws JPARSECException
        Transforms B1950 coordinates (FK4 system) to J2000 or another equinox, supposing that the object has no proper motion or is far away.
        Parameters:
        eq - Equatorial coordinates FK4 B1950.
        jdFK5 - The epoch of the output coordinates as a Julian day.
        jdFK4 - The epoch of observation as a Julian day, in case it is not B1950.
        eph - The ephemeris object selecting the precession algorithms.
        Returns:
        FK5 Jxxxx (jdFK5) coordinates.
        Throws:
        JPARSECException - Should not be thrown.

      • precessionNewcomb

        public static double[] precessionNewcomb(double from,
                         double to,
                         double[] p)
        Transforms coordinates for precession between two dates, using the method by Newcomb. This is an old method implemented for the transformation of coordinates between Bessel epochs, and it is not used in JPARSEC actively. Algorithm based on Woolard and Clemence 1966 (see AA suplement, page 107).
        Parameters:
        from - Julian date of reference.
        to - Julian date for the mean equinox of the output.
        p - Input equatorial coordinates.
        Returns:
        The output coordinates.

      • precessionIAU1976

        public static double[] precessionIAU1976(double from,
                         double to,
                         double[] p)
                                  throws JPARSECException
        Transforms coordinates for precession between J2000 and another date, using the method by Lieske. This is an old method implemented here to support old reduction models.
        Parameters:
        from - Julian day of input vector (equatorial rectangular) in TT.
        to - Julian day of output in TT. Either from or to must be equal to J2000.
        p - Input equatorial coordinates.
        Returns:
        The output coordinates.
        Throws:
        JPARSECException - If from and to are not equal to J2000 epoch.
